WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:12.580
&gt;&gt; Sharon Horowitz:
Good afternoon.

00:00:12.580 --> 00:00:14.940
Welcome to the African and
Middle Eastern Reading Room.

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:18.500
On behalf of the music division
and the Hebraic section,

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:21.520
let me thank you all for
coming to today's program.

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:23.510
My name is Sharon Horowitz.

00:00:23.510 --> 00:00:25.950
I'm a reference librarian
in the Hebraic section.

00:00:25.950 --> 00:00:30.040
The Hebraic section marks
its beginning in 1912

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:32.900
with the receipt of 10,000
Hebrew books and pamphlets,

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:36.220
whose purchase was
made possible by a gift

00:00:36.220 --> 00:00:39.360
from New York philanthropist,
Jacob Schiff.

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:42.330
From those humble beginnings,
our collections have grown

00:00:42.330 --> 00:00:47.060
to around 250,000 items in
Hebrew, Yiddish, Ladino,

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:50.400
Judeo-Persian, and other
Hebraic-script languages.

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:53.630
The Hebraic section also
includes an important collection

00:00:53.630 --> 00:00:56.450
of books in Ge'ez, Hark
[phonetic], and Tigrinya,

00:00:56.450 --> 00:00:59.640
the languages of
Ethiopia, past and present.

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:02.550
Our sections' holdings are
particularly strong in the areas

00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:06.810
of bible and Rabbinics, liturgy,
Hebrew language and literature,

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:08.500
[inaudible] and Jewish history.

00:01:08.500 --> 00:01:10.970
Two of our missions
in this division are

00:01:10.970 --> 00:01:12.770
to publicize our collections

00:01:12.770 --> 00:01:14.910
and to bring people
into the library.

00:01:14.910 --> 00:01:17.280
One way we accomplish
this second goal is

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:19.360
by holding lectures
and having programs

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:21.820
such as the one we are
hosting here today.

00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:24.260
And now, a word about
our speaker.

00:01:24.260 --> 00:01:27.300
Vivi Lachs is a social
and cultural historian,

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:29.290
a performer as well
as an academic.

00:01:29.290 --> 00:01:32.220
She completed her PhD in 2015

00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:34.370
from Royal Holloway
University of London.

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:38.320
She has given many academic
presentations focused

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:40.990
on ethnomusicology
and the acculturation

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:43.610
of Jewish immigrants
to English life.

00:01:43.610 --> 00:01:46.690
She has written both
academic and popular articles

00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:48.310
and has performed
throughout Europe.

00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:50.800
She has a wide experience
performing

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:53.780
as a Yiddish vocalist,
dance leader,

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:55.830
and among her
performance-related

00:01:55.830 --> 00:01:59.240
accomplishments, she has
organized a marching band

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:01.780
and chorus performing
Yiddish songs of protest

00:02:01.780 --> 00:02:06.280
from the late 19th Century by
the late Morris Winchevsky.

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:11.090
Vivi has been called the Yiddish
London folk song detective.

00:02:11.090 --> 00:02:13.330
She collects, performs,
translates

00:02:13.330 --> 00:02:16.060
and records Yiddish
songs about London.

00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:18.980
In her book, White Chapel
Noise, Jewish immigrant life

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:24.380
and Yiddish song and
verse, London 1884 to 1914,

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:30.260
Ms. Lachs researched
points to the similarities

00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:34.730
between these Yiddish folk
songs and English musical songs.

00:02:34.730 --> 00:02:36.620
Layers of cultural references

00:02:36.620 --> 00:02:39.950
in the Yiddish text are closely
analyzed and quoted to draw

00:02:39.950 --> 00:02:43.510
out the complex, yet intimate
histories they contain,

00:02:43.510 --> 00:02:45.270
offering new perspectives

00:02:45.270 --> 00:02:49.010
on Anglo-Jewish histography
in three main areas.

00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:52.170
Politics, sex, and religion.

00:02:52.170 --> 00:02:54.670
Two items of business,
before we begin.

