00:03:37.490 --> 00:03:38.790
[applause]

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:40.090
&gt;&gt; Vivi Lachs: I've
just [inaudible].

00:03:40.090 --> 00:03:41.390
Thank you very much, Sharon.

00:03:41.390 --> 00:03:43.870
It's lovely to be here
in this amazing building,

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:45.250
which I haven't been in before.

00:03:45.250 --> 00:03:47.860
I mean, obviously I've been
in the British library many,

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:50.420
many times, so I know
exactly what people do

00:03:50.420 --> 00:03:51.720
in these sort of buildings.

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:56.660
So, I'm going to tell you
a little bit about my book

00:03:56.660 --> 00:03:59.020
and hopefully entertain
you with it

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:03.510
and give you some ideas
from what it's about.

00:04:03.510 --> 00:04:05.410
So the book is called
White Chapel Noise,

00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:09.440
and the White Chapel is
an area of East London.

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:13.080
It's in the East End where
the immigrant population came

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:15.190
to from the mid-1880s.

00:04:15.190 --> 00:04:17.970
So Jewish immigrants
from Eastern Europe came

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:20.930
over to White Chapel,
and they spoke Yiddish,

00:04:20.930 --> 00:04:25.120
and that Yiddish culture
just infused the area

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:27.570
in this time from the mid-1880s.

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:30.170
And this is a picture from 1897,

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:33.050
and it's showing the
noise that's going on.

00:04:33.050 --> 00:04:36.540
And by noise, I don't
just mean the hubbub.

00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:40.770
I don't just mean the sort
of like the horses' hooves

00:04:40.770 --> 00:04:44.750
and the whirring of wheels
and the new motor cars.

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:51.350
It's people talking and people
shouting and people arguing

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:55.410
and people crying and
laughing and all that.

00:04:55.410 --> 00:05:00.310
But in particular, the noise
is people having arguments

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:03.270
with each other because there
were huge arguments going

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:05.540
on at this time.

00:05:05.540 --> 00:05:10.180
And one of the big issues for
all of these people was how

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:12.360
to acculturate to
English society.

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:13.950
Because they came
from Eastern Europe,

00:05:13.950 --> 00:05:16.330
and the culture was
very, very different,

00:05:16.330 --> 00:05:18.870
and they wanted obviously
to become English.

00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:21.170
Not only did they, the
immigrants, come over and want

00:05:21.170 --> 00:05:26.560
to be English, but also the
settled Jewish communities,

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:28.950
who had been there for
some decades already,

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:32.140
they really wanted these
immigrants to become English

00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:34.420
because they were a source
of acute embarrassment

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:37.640
to the Jewish community for
these very poor immigrants

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:39.360
to come along when they

00:05:39.360 --> 00:05:44.780
as a middle class society
had got Jewish emancipation,

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:48.510
and they wanted to hold onto
the gains that they'd made.

00:05:48.510 --> 00:05:55.460
So, the book is, it's in
two parts, essentially,

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:59.890
and the first part gives
you some contextual history.

00:05:59.890 --> 00:06:03.050
So the first part gives you
two particular histories.

00:06:03.050 --> 00:06:07.880
Firstly, it lays out the
labor history of the time,

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:10.170
and it looks at the radicals

00:06:10.170 --> 00:06:12.490
or the socialists
and the anarchists.

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:14.530
However, the particular
difference

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:18.360
in this history is it's looking
at the way poetry was used

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:21.160
as a strategy by the socialists.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:23.800
The second history
is the history

00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:26.080
of the Cockney Yiddish musical

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:29.080
as it was rather
affectionately known.

00:06:29.080 --> 00:06:32.120
And this is the musical
in Yiddish

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:34.930
in the east end of London.

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:39.820
And then, the second part
of the book is analysis

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:44.030
of what are called Kuplatan
[phonetic] couplets.

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:49.060
And these couplets come from
three genres, socialist poetry,

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:51.000
music-hall song,
and satirical verse,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.230
which I'll tell you
about in a minute.

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:56.300
There are three overarching
perspectives that cut

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:58.860
across this, and I've
just looked at the idea

00:06:58.860 --> 00:07:01.840
of anglicization of people
wanting to become English.

00:07:01.840 --> 00:07:05.530
The second large perspective
is that of transnationalism.

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:10.380
So although I chose material
that is very much about London

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:12.520
and about England, in fact,

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:16.460
it's also about a much wider
Yiddish-speaking world.

00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:19.710
And the third one is the culture
controversy, is the noise

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:22.200
of the argument of the
[foreign language spoken]

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:25.580
and the shouting and
the crying and those,

00:07:25.580 --> 00:07:29.370
it's what were they arguing
about, what was going on there.

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:33.330
And then the themes,
politics, sex, and religion.

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:35.920
You might think have been
written about quite a lot

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:39.950
but not from these sources
because from taking things

00:07:39.950 --> 00:07:43.990
from Yiddish is, first of
all, there's been a lot

00:07:43.990 --> 00:07:46.580
of Anglo-Jewish history
written, very,

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:49.110
very few Yiddish
sources have been used.

00:07:49.110 --> 00:07:52.070
So using those sources, you
get a very different view.

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:56.280
But secondly, the source I've
chosen are from popular culture.

00:07:56.280 --> 00:07:58.260
And if you're taking
sources from popular culture,

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:00.090
you're getting a
view from below,

00:08:00.090 --> 00:08:02.270
and you're really getting
into those arguments.

00:08:02.270 --> 00:08:04.090
So you're not getting
the official line.

00:08:04.090 --> 00:08:08.570
You're not getting minutes of
synagogue meetings or various,

00:08:08.570 --> 00:08:12.360
not they weren't arguments
in synagogue meetings,

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:15.820
but you are getting the things
that people are making fun of.

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.040
And if you look at what
people are making fun of,

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:20.040
you can see actually what's
really touching people,

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:22.120
especially the satirists.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:24.840
So, I'll start up
with the three genres.

00:08:24.840 --> 00:08:28.630
The first one is socialist
poetry, and I found this

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:30.730
in all sorts of publications.

00:08:30.730 --> 00:08:35.280
So we have the newspapers, the
Polish Yid or The Polish Jew,

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:36.920
[foreign language spoken],
The Worker's Friend.

00:08:36.920 --> 00:08:38.960
We have pamphlets.

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:43.620
For example, the one in the
top middle, I don't know

00:08:43.620 --> 00:08:46.140
if anyone can read that,
Mary [inaudible] you read it.

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:47.440
&gt;&gt; This Vetting System.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:48.960
&gt;&gt; Vivi Lachs: This
Vetting System.

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:52.840
So, we've got, so pamphlets
about politics going on,

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:55.280
and then we've got
song sheets as well,

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:58.690
like Yiddish [foreign language
spoken], which is a serious

00:08:58.690 --> 00:09:03.660
of Yiddish freedom, which is
a series of different songs.

00:09:03.660 --> 00:09:05.700
So this is, and I've
found lots and lots

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:07.590
and lots of this material.

00:09:07.590 --> 00:09:09.620
I'll tell you how
many in a minute.

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:13.330
The second genre
is musical songs.

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:16.950
And these were produced in
song sheets and song books.

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:19.480
So at the top left
you'll see a song sheet,

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:21.200
so this is a little bit
of a tattered one there.

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:23.680
That's from the National
Library of Israel.

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:27.130
In the middle you see a
program, a theater program,

00:09:27.130 --> 00:09:30.680
which has got a cross-dressed
actress on the front.

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:33.580
On the bottom right,
you have a song book

00:09:33.580 --> 00:09:36.580
which tells us there are
150 pages and 100 songs.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:40.740
Actually they can't count, there
are 102 songs in that book.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:43.380
And that was because
it was pulling lots

00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:45.930
of pamphlets together, which
is sort of what they did.

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:48.230
And there are some pages
from that at the bottom.

00:09:48.230 --> 00:09:50.470
So these are all the songs
that were being song,

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:53.420
and when we start getting
into them, we can have a bit

00:09:53.420 --> 00:09:57.510
of a laugh and possibly a bit
of a cry as well over them.

00:09:57.510 --> 00:10:01.410
And finally, the third
genre is satirical verse,

00:10:01.410 --> 00:10:04.120
and people were writing
satirical verse everywhere.

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:08.320
Satire is a fantastic genre
to look at for a historian,

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:10.530
because although you have
to go digging a bit to find

00:10:10.530 --> 00:10:13.980
out actually what's going on
there, you really get to see

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:18.010
where people are really
like having a punisher,

00:10:18.010 --> 00:10:20.800
of having a go at each other.

00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:26.610
So, what I'm going to do is
I'm going to have a look at all

00:10:26.610 --> 00:10:29.840
of these three perspectives
and show you where they come

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:31.430
in to a couple of texts.

00:10:31.430 --> 00:10:33.960
So I've mentioned
Anglicization, Transnationalism,

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:37.090
and the cultural noise,
and now I'm going to look

00:10:37.090 --> 00:10:39.130
at two different texts.

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:42.810
The first one is a poem
by Morris Winchevsky,

00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:45.670
who we'll come across a
little bit later, again,

00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:48.930
and this is a poem
called London bay nakht.

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:52.230
And I'll start off
by looking at it.

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:54.700
In fact, I'll start off
by singing it to you.

00:10:54.700 --> 00:10:56.000
How about that?

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.400
And then we'll have a
look at what's going on.

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:00.510
So it's about street lights.

00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:46.040
[ Singing ]

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:48.680
And it goes on so all the
things that the streetlights see

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:51.300
and the streetlights don't see.

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:55.290
So they don't see, they see
the streets, but they don't,

00:11:55.290 --> 00:11:57.930
and the walls of the buildings,

00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:00.210
but they don't see the
unemployment and the poverty

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.940
and the homelessness,
and the difficulty

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:04.620
of being a new immigrant
in the city.

00:12:04.620 --> 00:12:08.200
And the song then
compares these streetlights

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:11.760
to the London committee
and the London committee

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:16.080
who were the Jewish board
of guardians were people

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:17.910
who were supporting
the immigrants.

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:21.580
However, what you'll see is
there's a line that goes,

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:24.960
have you seen a greener
Jew wandering alone.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:28.530
In verse two, the last line of
that verse, too new an immigrant

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:30.050
to be helped by the
London committee,

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:32.720
and that too new an immigrant
is because the London Board

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:35.510
of Guardians wouldn't support
immigrants until they'd been

00:12:35.510 --> 00:12:38.190
in Britain for six months.

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:40.860
So if you came to Britain
and you didn't have a job

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:44.340
and you didn't have family
there and you didn't have a way

00:12:44.340 --> 00:12:47.900
of keeping yourself, then in
fact, you would have fallen

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:51.220
into a huge poverty gap because
there would be no support

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:54.660
for you on an institutional
level.

00:12:54.660 --> 00:12:58.420
So, looking at that
content, it's very,

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:01.370
very much about England
and about Anglicization

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:04.020
because it's engaging
with English culture

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:06.330
and English [inaudible].

00:13:06.330 --> 00:13:11.600
However, there's also a very
interesting transnational part

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:16.650
of this, and that is this poem
was written by Winchevsky,

00:13:16.650 --> 00:13:19.080
who wasn't really a poet
when he was writing this.

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:21.870
He was just a beginning
poet, and he wrote this

00:13:21.870 --> 00:13:24.370
in the structure of a poem
by Mietlev [phonetic],

00:13:24.370 --> 00:13:25.910
who was a Russian poet,

00:13:25.910 --> 00:13:29.600
and Mietlev wrote a poem
called Fonarichi [phonetic],

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:30.930
Street Lights.

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:34.780
And Mietlev's poem also had
street lights see some things

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:36.080
and don't see other things.

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:39.230
The things they saw though,
the things they didn't see

00:13:39.230 --> 00:13:43.090
that were sort of hidden to
the street lights were a couple

00:13:43.090 --> 00:13:47.240
in love, a woman who's
just been abandoned.

00:13:47.240 --> 00:13:49.800
They were things that
were socially important,

00:13:49.800 --> 00:13:51.840
but they weren't
politically important,

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:55.590
and so Winchevsky came along
and threw a punch behind it,

00:13:55.590 --> 00:13:59.020
putting some political
importance to this.

00:13:59.020 --> 00:14:04.590
So, in a way that was a
criticism of Mietlev's poem,

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:07.170
but it also like
gave him a structure

00:14:07.170 --> 00:14:08.860
to write a better poem too.

00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:12.070
The other things
that's transnational

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:14.890
about this that's very
interesting is this poem was

00:14:14.890 --> 00:14:18.860
published in New York, but you
couldn't really publish a poem

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:21.180
in New York called
London bay nakht.

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:22.620
I mean who was going to read it?

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:25.740
So they changed the name of it

00:14:25.740 --> 00:14:27.810
to [foreign language
spoken] street lights.

00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:31.090
And they couldn't really
have the London committee.

00:14:31.090 --> 00:14:33.260
So that was changed to [foreign
language spoken] street light.

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:41.900
The New York Eighth Street folk,
which is on the lower east side.

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:46.270
The interesting thing about this
is that if you can have a poem

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:49.820
or a song that is written
and published and performed

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:52.340
in Britain and then in a
completely different place

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:57.380
in New York, you can
make some claim to saying

00:14:57.380 --> 00:15:00.590
that the experience in
both these places is very,

00:15:00.590 --> 00:15:01.890
very similar.

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:04.750
So we have a transnational
culture of immigrants going

00:15:04.750 --> 00:15:07.530
to different places and actually
absorbing the same popular

00:15:07.530 --> 00:15:10.100
culture, being given that
same popular culture.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:14.530
I also look at one other
song that also engages

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:18.160
with these different
transnationalism cultural

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:20.770
controversy and Anglicization.

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:26.740
And this one, I'm
actually only going

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:29.450
to look particularly
and Anglicization.

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:33.110
And that is that term Cockney
Yiddish that's used and just try

00:15:33.110 --> 00:15:35.450
and describe what
Cockney Yiddish is.

00:15:35.450 --> 00:15:38.980
Now, first of all in
the transnational front,

00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:40.280
this is a song called
[foreign language spoken].

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:42.950
It's rather a curious
Yiddish name.

00:15:42.950 --> 00:15:47.330
I'm not going to go into that at
the moment, that's in the book,

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:50.490
but I will say is that the
original [foreign language

00:15:50.490 --> 00:15:54.510
spoken] was written by a man
called Abraham Goldsfaden,

00:15:54.510 --> 00:15:59.530
and Goldsfaden was a father
of the Yiddish theater.

00:15:59.530 --> 00:16:02.490
Now, he wrote this
about a decade before

00:16:02.490 --> 00:16:07.980
or actually probably more, and
this was written around 1900's.

00:16:07.980 --> 00:16:12.900
It was probably written in
about 1880 by Goldsfaden,

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:17.120
and Goldsfaden's song,
everybody would have known,

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:18.460
people loved Goldsfaden.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:20.780
So if you produce a song
in London with a title

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:24.190
that everyone knows, everyone's
already got some expectations,

00:16:24.190 --> 00:16:25.700
so they sort of know
what's going to happen.

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:29.790
Now the Goldsfaden's song is
about a tired, dispirited Jew

00:16:29.790 --> 00:16:32.670
who is wandering around
looking for a homeland,

00:16:32.670 --> 00:16:38.930
this archetypal figure
of the wandering Jew,

00:16:38.930 --> 00:16:41.190
and his answer is,
[foreign language spoken],

00:16:41.190 --> 00:16:46.370
go back to the Jewish
homelands of Zion.

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:47.670
The [foreign language spoken]

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:50.400
in London is not saying
anything of the sort.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:52.960
But that also has an
archetypal Jew that's wandering

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:54.940
around homeless and penniless,

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:58.090
but what the [foreign
language spoken] the world

00:16:58.090 --> 00:17:01.450
to go back is Eastern Europe.

00:17:01.450 --> 00:17:06.400
So it's a curious poem that
again, a song that really

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:11.320
like is part of British
culture and talks about Britain.

00:17:11.320 --> 00:17:14.140
But let's have a look
at the Cockney Yiddish.

00:17:14.140 --> 00:17:20.630
Git a blik in der leyn vet
interest rate dort zen file

00:17:20.630 --> 00:17:25.380
mentshn shteyen aropgelozt
demonstrate kop.

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:28.100
Tsvishn zey in dermit

00:17:28.100 --> 00:17:35.060
in der korner goldston strit
shteyt a griner yid un kukt oys

00:17:35.060 --> 00:17:37.120
a dzhob.

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:41.100
So we've got a few words here
in fact, but particularly,

00:17:41.100 --> 00:17:43.050
the first line git
a blik in der leyn,

00:17:43.050 --> 00:17:46.000
der leyn was Petticoat
Lane, which was the market.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.590
Okay. But of course you're
going to use a word like leyn.

00:17:48.590 --> 00:17:51.490
You wouldn't change that,
but we've got in der--

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:52.790
I'm sorry, what am I knocking--

00:17:52.790 --> 00:17:56.710
we've got in der korner
of goldston strit.

00:17:56.710 --> 00:17:58.090
Well the words for corner

00:17:58.090 --> 00:18:01.230
in Yiddish [foreign
language spoken].

00:18:01.230 --> 00:18:02.730
It's not korner.

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:04.230
Korner is an English word.

00:18:04.230 --> 00:18:06.640
And so they're throwing
in an English word

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:09.460
for no particular reason really.

00:18:09.460 --> 00:18:12.070
Have another look
at the next verse.

00:18:12.070 --> 00:18:19.240
A yolk hot bald derkent az
a griner dort gayt un hot

00:18:19.240 --> 00:18:26.290
oysgetsoygn zayne hent un
hot im bavelkomt mit a fayt.

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:30.490
So here you can see quite
clearly there's lots of words

00:18:30.490 --> 00:18:32.530
for welcome in Yiddish.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:35.930
[Foreign language spoken]
is not a Yiddish word.

00:18:35.930 --> 00:18:40.030
It's an English word being
Yiddish-sized by putting a sort

00:18:40.030 --> 00:18:42.120
of Yiddish inflection on it.

00:18:42.120 --> 00:18:45.490
The word fight is also
not a Yiddish word.

00:18:45.490 --> 00:18:47.010
It's an English word,
and in fact,

00:18:47.010 --> 00:18:48.800
the word [foreign language
spoken], which it rhymes

00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:52.110
with is changed from gayts
to giyts to make it rhyme,

00:18:52.110 --> 00:18:55.080
which is a different way
of pronouncing the Yiddish.

00:18:55.080 --> 00:18:58.050
So this sort of Englishness
creeping

00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:00.730
into the songs makes
them very much

00:19:00.730 --> 00:19:03.430
as a part of English culture.

00:19:03.430 --> 00:19:10.540
So, I'm now going to talk about
the themes of politics, sex,

00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:13.430
and religion, and I'm going to
give you a couple of example

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:18.560
on each of them by looking at
a couple of different songs

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:21.870
and get a sense of what
we can sort of glean

00:19:21.870 --> 00:19:24.470
from the history in these songs.

00:19:24.470 --> 00:19:27.970
So we're going to stay
with Morris Winchevsky,

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:33.170
who wrote a poem called
Akhdes, and this poem, Akhdes,

00:19:33.170 --> 00:19:35.850
became very popular later.

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:37.780
It became a very popular poem,

00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:41.630
and in fact in the
1920's it was made

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:43.230
into a song called
[foreign language spoken].

00:19:43.230 --> 00:19:46.510
Some of you might have heard--

00:19:46.510 --> 00:19:49.040
[ Singing ]

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:51.720
So, but that was
a completely song.

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:53.930
The [foreign language
spoken] is a nice happy,

00:19:53.930 --> 00:19:58.340
clappy song that they claim
came from the Winchevsky.

00:19:58.340 --> 00:20:00.790
Winchevsky's poem is a satire.

00:20:00.790 --> 00:20:04.610
It's very funny, but
it's not happy clappy.

00:20:04.610 --> 00:20:06.630
And we'll have a
look at the poem

00:20:06.630 --> 00:20:08.880
and see what it's telling us.

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:13.860
So the poem says,
we are all united.

00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:16.100
Whether we've got
a lot or a little.

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:18.780
We all pray from the
same prayer book.

00:20:18.780 --> 00:20:21.310
We're all united whether
we're cutting coupons

00:20:21.310 --> 00:20:23.000
or we're cutting trousers.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.730
I mean whether you're poor
or rich, we're all united.

00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:28.630
We're all united whether
you've got short [inaudible],

00:20:28.630 --> 00:20:32.300
the sidecurls, the [inaudible]
and other groups have

00:20:32.300 --> 00:20:34.170
or whether we've got long ones,

00:20:34.170 --> 00:20:35.750
or whether we put
them behind our ears

00:20:35.750 --> 00:20:37.830
or whether we have
them hanging straight.

00:20:37.830 --> 00:20:41.900
Whether we're hungry or
whether we're satisfied,

00:20:41.900 --> 00:20:47.640
we're all united just like all
these things that are united.

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:49.810
But when you look at
it a bit more closely,

00:20:49.810 --> 00:20:51.360
you say well actually
what's going on there

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:54.590
because there's something
very specific going on here.

00:20:54.590 --> 00:20:56.060
Winchevsky is writing in London.

00:20:56.060 --> 00:20:59.570
He was in London for 15 years,
and he's writing about politics.

00:20:59.570 --> 00:21:04.620
So, first of all, anyone
recognize this chap?

00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:06.230
Karl Marx.

00:21:06.230 --> 00:21:12.000
Karl Marx was the inspiration
to many of the socialists,

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:21.230
and his famous line about unity
was workers of the world unite.

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:22.530
It's particular important

00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:26.980
because what Winchevsky
is saying in his poem is

00:21:26.980 --> 00:21:28.920
that actually it's not workers.

00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:32.980
No, the aristocracy and
the workers are united.

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:37.310
It's very antisocialist because
what Winchevsky is saying

00:21:37.310 --> 00:21:40.070
and the socialists say is
the unity does not come

00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:41.370
from ethnicity.

00:21:41.370 --> 00:21:44.650
Just because you all happen to
be Jews, that creates no unity.

00:21:44.650 --> 00:21:46.680
The unity is across class,

00:21:46.680 --> 00:21:49.060
and it doesn't matter
what religion you are.

00:21:49.060 --> 00:21:54.120
So, in that sense, we can see
that what this is going to do

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:56.490
as soon as he has a poem called
united, we know it's going

00:21:56.490 --> 00:21:57.960
to turn everything on its head.

00:21:57.960 --> 00:22:03.370
We all pray from the same
prayer book is a phrase,

00:22:03.370 --> 00:22:07.040
we all sing from the same hymn
sheet, but actually he's using

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:10.120
that phrase but being
quite clever about it.

00:22:10.120 --> 00:22:14.750
A month prior to this poem being
written was the publication

00:22:14.750 --> 00:22:16.240
of the Single's Pray Book.

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:18.860
And the Single's Prayer
book was published

00:22:18.860 --> 00:22:22.100
for the Anglo-Jewish
community who were established

00:22:22.100 --> 00:22:28.160
in middle class, and
they spoke English.

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:32.450
The immigrants largely
didn't speak English,

00:22:32.450 --> 00:22:33.750
they spoke Yiddish.

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:37.060
So a brand-new translation,
beautiful as it was,

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:43.480
and a really important new
addition to Anglo-Jewish

00:22:43.480 --> 00:22:47.650
and Anglo-Jewish orthodoxy
wasn't particularly a very

00:22:47.650 --> 00:22:49.680
useful addition to
the immigrants

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:55.150
so they certainly
didn't create unity.

00:22:55.150 --> 00:22:57.800
So we're also united if
you're cutting trousers

00:22:57.800 --> 00:22:59.120
or you're cutting coupons.

00:22:59.120 --> 00:23:03.420
Well cutting trousers means
that you are what most Jews

00:23:03.420 --> 00:23:07.600
in the East End were at this
time, a large percentage worked

00:23:07.600 --> 00:23:10.490
in sweatshops as tailors
[foreign language spoken].

00:23:10.490 --> 00:23:14.820
So, these people,
they're cutting trousers,

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:16.380
they're being manufacturers,

00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:19.940
they're using their
hands and producing.

00:23:19.940 --> 00:23:21.920
Cutting coupons refers

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:26.800
to the Jewish [inaudible]
guardians giving handouts.

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:29.480
So they, later on they gave
money, but at this stage,

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:31.800
in fact two years after
this had changed to money,

00:23:31.800 --> 00:23:35.660
so we can really see
how much it was topical

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:37.810
that this time they're
giving coupons.

00:23:37.810 --> 00:23:41.330
So the socialists are
saying don't take handouts.

00:23:41.330 --> 00:23:42.850
That is not the way
to be a worker.

00:23:42.850 --> 00:23:46.110
The way to be a worker is
to work with your hands

00:23:46.110 --> 00:23:50.570
and to be a part of
the working class.

00:23:51.750 --> 00:23:57.880
Finally, using the word unity
is particularly important

00:23:57.880 --> 00:24:03.470
because six months
before this, there was a,

00:24:03.470 --> 00:24:07.480
six months before this the
chief rabbi, Nathan Adler, died,

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:10.910
and there was a lot of talk
about who was going to take over

00:24:10.910 --> 00:24:15.470
and where they would live and
what sorts of position they'd do

00:24:15.470 --> 00:24:18.760
and what they'd be involved
in, and under the title

00:24:18.760 --> 00:24:22.960
that was the letters page,
unity not uniformity.

00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:27.160
And under that title, there
were lots and lots and lots

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:30.790
of letters about what was going
to happen, and it's almost

00:24:30.790 --> 00:24:33.790
like Winchevsky in his
poem, he's adding to that.

00:24:33.790 --> 00:24:35.090
This is his contribution.

00:24:35.090 --> 00:24:37.860
Those letters were produced
in the Jewish chronicle.

00:24:37.860 --> 00:24:40.920
Winchevsky's letter was produced

00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:42.550
in the [foreign language
spoken], The Worker's Friend,

00:24:42.550 --> 00:24:44.210
but essentially it is if you

00:24:44.210 --> 00:24:46.890
like his contribution
to that debate.

00:24:46.890 --> 00:24:50.740
So when you look at a song like
this, you can see all the layers

00:24:50.740 --> 00:24:53.790
of satire, and then when
you sing, when you go back

00:24:53.790 --> 00:24:57.120
and sing [foreign language
spoken], again, you can bear

00:24:57.120 --> 00:25:01.270
in mind that it comes from
a good strong history.

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:06.490
Morris Winchevsky, in terms
of strategy for the poetry,

00:25:06.490 --> 00:25:10.550
so we saw earlier on that he
wrote a poem called London bay

00:25:10.550 --> 00:25:13.580
nakht, which was part of what
was called London [inaudible].

00:25:13.580 --> 00:25:15.560
He wrote another poem called
[foreign language spoken],

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:19.490
Three Sisters, about
three girls in poverty.

00:25:19.490 --> 00:25:20.960
One's selling shoelaces.

00:25:20.960 --> 00:25:22.540
One is selling flowers.

00:25:22.540 --> 00:25:25.230
And the other is
selling herself.

00:25:25.230 --> 00:25:27.280
And he puts a socialist message

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:30.680
by the girls not blaming each
other but blaming society,

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:34.150
by blaming devout and
[foreign language spoken].

00:25:34.150 --> 00:25:38.810
They blame the society for them
having to do this sort of work

00:25:38.810 --> 00:25:40.480
because of their poverty.

00:25:40.480 --> 00:25:43.450
So these are poems about
terrible properties

00:25:43.450 --> 00:25:45.960
and getting people
to feel something.

00:25:45.960 --> 00:25:48.860
The poem that we have
about London bay nakht

00:25:48.860 --> 00:25:51.500
as well was also about
people in poverty.

00:25:51.500 --> 00:25:55.690
Then we have the satirical
poem, but he had other poetry

00:25:55.690 --> 00:25:57.270
that he wrote as well.

00:25:57.270 --> 00:25:59.980
And this is one called
Tsum arbayter fraynd.

00:25:59.980 --> 00:26:01.820
And as you see from the lyrics,

00:26:01.820 --> 00:26:05.460
this is really socialist
polemic.

00:26:05.460 --> 00:26:07.190
It's about alienation.

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:13.640
People who are producing are
not the same people who consume.

00:26:13.640 --> 00:26:17.510
So, I'm going to
sing you one verse.

00:26:17.510 --> 00:26:46.260
[ Singing ]

00:26:46.260 --> 00:26:54.180
It's particularly interesting in
terms of the melody of the song

00:26:54.180 --> 00:26:58.200
because [foreign language
spoken] who was a Yiddish sort

00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:03.950
of like critic and
writer came across girls

00:27:03.950 --> 00:27:06.070
in a factor singing this song.

00:27:06.070 --> 00:27:07.580
This is actually a picture
of a factory in Leeds,

00:27:07.580 --> 00:27:10.140
but he came across girls
singing this song in a factory

00:27:10.140 --> 00:27:14.690
in Belarus, and this
is what he said.

00:27:14.690 --> 00:27:18.870
He said the tune was
haunting, solemn and haunting.

00:27:18.870 --> 00:27:22.010
The machines knocked and
the song carried, demanded,

00:27:22.010 --> 00:27:24.910
punished, and welcomes
the arbayter fraynd.

00:27:24.910 --> 00:27:27.280
I heard this song many
times in the factories.

00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:29.270
It was sung heartily
and with feeling.

00:27:29.270 --> 00:27:32.650
At times, a factory girl
would get a tear in her eye,

00:27:32.650 --> 00:27:34.610
but after they finished
singing the atmosphere,

00:27:34.610 --> 00:27:40.050
it was continuously oppressive,
would simply become cleansed.

00:27:40.050 --> 00:27:44.760
So another strategy that
he has was to create songs

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:48.240
that were going to help people
through the day, that were going

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:50.820
to encourage them to keep going.

00:27:50.820 --> 00:27:55.830
And finally, the sort of songs
he wrote were also hymns to go

00:27:55.830 --> 00:27:59.610
out onto the streets for
union action and to march the

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:01.910
in di gasn, tsu di masn.

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:06.110
Fun badrikte feltker-rasn
ruft der frayhaytsgayst.

00:28:06.110 --> 00:28:07.730
Ikh bring vafn far dem shlafn.

00:28:07.730 --> 00:28:11.560
Ikh bafray di arbet-shklafn
un ikh makh zey drayst.

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:14.770
So they're out there chanting
and singing the songs,

00:28:14.770 --> 00:28:18.470
and again, they refer to
things that are going on,

00:28:18.470 --> 00:28:21.630
in particular strike
action in London.

00:28:21.630 --> 00:28:24.070
So Albert [inaudible] asking
for systematic work was

00:28:24.070 --> 00:28:26.880
because they wanted
to end out work,

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:28.640
which meant that
people would take work

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:31.410
in and cut union rates.

00:28:31.410 --> 00:28:32.710
And also [foreign
language spoken]

00:28:32.710 --> 00:28:38.150
because on these strikes
they weren't solely strikes

00:28:38.150 --> 00:28:41.890
from the Jewish tailors or the
Jewish shoe and bootmakers,

00:28:41.890 --> 00:28:46.200
but they were actually strikes
where the non-Jewish dockers,

00:28:46.200 --> 00:28:48.610
the English dockers were
also, and the Irish dockers,

00:28:48.610 --> 00:28:52.210
were also coming
in to join them.

00:28:52.210 --> 00:28:56.620
So, moving on now
to the theme of sex.

00:28:56.620 --> 00:28:59.750
And I found about
80 musical songs,

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:03.690
and out of those 80 musical
songs that mentioned London,

00:29:03.690 --> 00:29:06.910
around 47 of them mentioned sex.

00:29:06.910 --> 00:29:09.930
Now, you might say, that's
obvious in the musical

00:29:09.930 --> 00:29:11.640
because let's have a
look at this picture

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:12.940
that we've got in front of us.

00:29:12.940 --> 00:29:17.880
On the stage, we have a very
stereotyped Jewish man and woman

00:29:17.880 --> 00:29:19.470
who looked like they're in
a [foreign language spoken]

00:29:19.470 --> 00:29:22.830
or in a very sort of stereotyped
version of the [inaudible].

00:29:22.830 --> 00:29:26.750
Up in the gallery, we've
got some rather drunken lads

00:29:26.750 --> 00:29:28.880
who clearly aren't being
terribly entertained

00:29:28.880 --> 00:29:31.070
by what's on the stage.

00:29:31.070 --> 00:29:34.920
The orchestra seems to me
not keeping very good time,

00:29:34.920 --> 00:29:38.890
and instead of sitting on chairs
as one would in the theatre,

00:29:38.890 --> 00:29:41.790
the front row is full of beds

00:29:41.790 --> 00:29:43.850
that people are camoodling
[phonetic] on.

00:29:43.850 --> 00:29:49.320
Now this is a satirical cartoon
that's on the front cover

00:29:49.320 --> 00:29:51.770
of a journal called [foreign
language spoken], the blofer.

00:29:51.770 --> 00:29:58.420
It was produced between 1911
and 1913, and all the things,

00:29:58.420 --> 00:30:02.580
you know, obviously you take
satire with a pinch of salt,

00:30:02.580 --> 00:30:07.770
but there's always
an element of truth.

00:30:07.770 --> 00:30:12.270
But not everyone is writing
silly songs for the music call

00:30:12.270 --> 00:30:13.930
to entertain those lads.

00:30:13.930 --> 00:30:17.320
Some of the songs are actually
very, very moving songs,

00:30:17.320 --> 00:30:21.230
and this song by Joseph
Markevitch tells a story

00:30:21.230 --> 00:30:23.080
of a woman in Eastern Europe

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:25.260
who has been abandoned
by her husband.

00:30:25.260 --> 00:30:28.680
He comes over to
London, and he disappears

00:30:28.680 --> 00:30:32.290
into the 150,000 immigrants
that are in the streets

00:30:32.290 --> 00:30:37.340
of London's east end, and she's
writing to him, getting more

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:41.220
and more upset, saying,
you know, help me,

00:30:41.220 --> 00:30:44.510
we need help, and
the chorus goes--

00:30:44.510 --> 00:31:03.070
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:31:03.070 --> 00:31:04.370
And what you'll find
is that everyone

00:31:04.370 --> 00:31:06.890
in the audience would
have been in tears.

00:31:06.890 --> 00:31:08.190
They would have been crying

00:31:08.190 --> 00:31:10.540
because they all knew
people like this.

00:31:10.540 --> 00:31:12.650
They knew people that
were abandoned in Russia.

00:31:12.650 --> 00:31:14.770
They knew people that
were abandoned in Britain

00:31:14.770 --> 00:31:18.600
as their husbands came
over here and disappeared

00:31:18.600 --> 00:31:21.720
into a much larger low east side

00:31:21.720 --> 00:31:23.940
or anywhere else
those immigrants came

00:31:23.940 --> 00:31:30.110
to in the U.S. However,
most of the songs

00:31:30.110 --> 00:31:31.410
that were being performed

00:31:31.410 --> 00:31:35.730
in the music hall were pretty
much geared towards those lads

00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:37.140
in the audience, and one

00:31:37.140 --> 00:31:41.950
of these songs was a song called
Vus geyst nisht aheym sore-gitl.

00:31:41.950 --> 00:31:45.770
Does that sound familiar
to anyone?

00:31:45.770 --> 00:31:47.150
Won't you Come Home.

00:31:47.150 --> 00:31:49.220
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:31:49.220 --> 00:31:51.210
There we go, how does it go?

00:31:51.210 --> 00:31:54.700
Won't you come home girl, baby?

00:31:54.700 --> 00:31:57.510
Won't you come home?

00:31:57.510 --> 00:32:06.040
[ Singing ]

00:32:06.040 --> 00:32:08.830
So, it's, I mean, you
know, this is a known song,

00:32:08.830 --> 00:32:12.240
and it was a known song in 1905.

00:32:12.240 --> 00:32:17.960
So, but hang on a second,
this is slightly different.

00:32:17.960 --> 00:32:22.000
[Inaudible] Bill Bailey,
Sore is Sara, right.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.490
So let's have a look at how
the lyrics go on this one,

00:32:25.490 --> 00:32:28.250
and I'm going to sing you
the first versus and chorus.

00:32:28.250 --> 00:32:32.510
In fact, I'm just going to
sing it to you, I think.

00:32:32.510 --> 00:33:36.690
[ Singing ]

00:33:36.690 --> 00:33:41.210
Everyone. Oh Sore-gitl.

00:33:41.210 --> 00:33:42.510
Come home.

00:33:42.510 --> 00:33:46.310
You're being so embarrassing
there.

00:33:46.310 --> 00:33:48.960
Gallivanting with all the boys.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:50.690
Gallivanting with all the guys.

00:33:50.690 --> 00:33:53.040
You know, Sore-gitl,
they're all looking

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:55.070
at you and laughing at you.

00:33:55.070 --> 00:33:56.370
You know, Sore-gitl,
they're looking

00:33:56.370 --> 00:33:58.760
at us and laughing at us.

00:33:58.760 --> 00:34:01.030
Oh, you know Sore-gitl
they're all looking

00:34:01.030 --> 00:34:03.510
at me and laughing at me.

00:34:03.510 --> 00:34:28.470
[ Singing ]

00:34:28.470 --> 00:34:31.290
Won't you come home, Sore-gitl.

00:34:31.290 --> 00:34:33.520
Won't you come home.

00:34:33.520 --> 00:34:38.520
You know, I'm not
that kind of lad.

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:40.440
Listen to what I tell you.

00:34:40.440 --> 00:34:42.080
Hear from my tone.

00:34:42.080 --> 00:34:46.510
It all does along
when I get so sad.

00:34:46.510 --> 00:35:10.510
[ Singing ]

00:35:10.510 --> 00:35:15.170
[ Applause ]

00:35:15.170 --> 00:35:20.650
So we have here a performance of
a chap looking frightfully silly

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:23.690
on the stage, and the
question that we have

00:35:23.690 --> 00:35:27.690
to ask then is why is Norger
[phonetic] who wrote this song

00:35:27.690 --> 00:35:31.930
and performing this song doing
something that makes him look

00:35:31.930 --> 00:35:34.230
so silly on the stage.

00:35:34.230 --> 00:35:39.690
And the music hall is really
about cathartic experience.

00:35:39.690 --> 00:35:42.270
It's about people
laughing and people crying

00:35:42.270 --> 00:35:44.260
and people being able
to get their emotions

00:35:44.260 --> 00:35:46.980
out when they're living in a
situation that's actually very,

00:35:46.980 --> 00:35:49.950
very difficult, that's
struggling to make ends meet.

00:35:49.950 --> 00:35:52.540
So let's have a look at
what might be the cathartic

00:35:52.540 --> 00:35:54.770
experiences for the
men in the audience

00:35:54.770 --> 00:35:56.220
and for the women
in the audience.

00:35:56.220 --> 00:35:58.750
So a man comes over
from Eastern Europe,

00:35:58.750 --> 00:36:00.370
and he can't keep
his family there.

00:36:00.370 --> 00:36:02.590
They haven't got enough to eat.

00:36:02.590 --> 00:36:06.370
They come over to London
or indeed to New York,

00:36:06.370 --> 00:36:11.130
but to London, and they still
can't make ends meet in London.

00:36:11.130 --> 00:36:15.170
So they, the wife also
brings work in at home,

00:36:15.170 --> 00:36:18.250
and they still come, and they
bring in a lodger, a boarder,

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:21.150
to help pay the rent, and
they're still not making enough.

00:36:21.150 --> 00:36:25.360
They're really struggling
just to make ends meet.

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:30.230
And so the man, who is the wager
earner and the bread winner,

00:36:30.230 --> 00:36:33.920
is feeling like his position
as head of the household is

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:38.750
in danger, that he is like
no longer the patriarch

00:36:38.750 --> 00:36:42.920
as he can't actually do what the
head of the household is meant

00:36:42.920 --> 00:36:45.080
to do, which is to be
able to feed his children.

00:36:45.080 --> 00:36:49.120
And then he comes to the music
hall, and he sees someone

00:36:49.120 --> 00:36:52.720
on stage who is so much
more pathetic than he is.

00:36:52.720 --> 00:36:54.880
And he laughs.

00:36:54.880 --> 00:36:56.350
And what about women?

00:36:56.350 --> 00:36:58.400
So women come to the music hall,

00:36:58.400 --> 00:37:02.810
and they're working
extremely hard,

00:37:02.810 --> 00:37:04.640
and they're keeping
the household,

00:37:04.640 --> 00:37:06.730
and they're looking
after the children.

00:37:06.730 --> 00:37:08.130
And they come to the music halls

00:37:08.130 --> 00:37:11.470
and they see a woman
gallivanting with other chaps

00:37:11.470 --> 00:37:13.900
and wandering around
London city,

00:37:13.900 --> 00:37:18.410
and they go [foreign language
spoken], if only, I had the time

00:37:18.410 --> 00:37:20.690
to have an affair with someone.

00:37:20.690 --> 00:37:25.940
So, we're setting up a situation
where people can feel something,

00:37:25.940 --> 00:37:29.150
and it gives us a sense of
this is not just mimicking the

00:37:29.150 --> 00:37:32.850
English musical, but it's
saying something very specific

00:37:32.850 --> 00:37:35.430
about the immigrants'
experience.

00:37:35.430 --> 00:37:39.520
Okay, so I'm going to move
now to the theme of religion.

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:43.750
And everybody is
writing about religion.

00:37:43.750 --> 00:37:47.110
The socialists are
either haranguing religion

00:37:47.110 --> 00:37:49.970
or they're using religious
structures to make lots

00:37:49.970 --> 00:37:52.130
of points about socialism.

00:37:52.130 --> 00:37:57.670
The music hall is making sort
of really quite moving points

00:37:57.670 --> 00:38:00.450
about people becoming
more secular

00:38:00.450 --> 00:38:02.940
and losing their
connection to religion

00:38:02.940 --> 00:38:06.470
and the [inaudible]
writers, the satirists,

00:38:06.470 --> 00:38:09.450
are having field days around it.

00:38:09.450 --> 00:38:15.330
So, I'm going to have a look
at two texts around this.

00:38:15.330 --> 00:38:19.860
So, the first text is by a
guy called Avrom Margolin,

00:38:19.860 --> 00:38:21.840
Dr. Avrom Margolin, who is
the editor of Der blofer,

00:38:21.840 --> 00:38:26.960
but he was actually a
doctor, a medical doctor.

00:38:26.960 --> 00:38:31.100
And he wrote something
called A pekl neviyes.

00:38:31.100 --> 00:38:34.410
Now the connection with religion
is a little bit tangential,

00:38:34.410 --> 00:38:35.710
but we'll see.

00:38:35.710 --> 00:38:38.510
A pekl neviyes means a bunch
of prophesies or a bundle

00:38:38.510 --> 00:38:41.460
of prophesies, and it's based
on a chapter from Ezekiel,

00:38:41.460 --> 00:38:45.560
which describes the
war to end all wars,

00:38:45.560 --> 00:38:49.100
and it starts off like this.

00:38:51.510 --> 00:39:10.710
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:39:10.710 --> 00:39:13.010
So he sets up there's
something terrible going

00:39:13.010 --> 00:39:14.310
to happen in White Chapel.

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:15.800
There's going to be a
war to end all wars.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:18.740
So let's have a look at what
that war was going to be.

00:39:18.740 --> 00:39:22.430
And he continues
his 166-line stanza

00:39:22.430 --> 00:39:25.390
which has 18 people
in the community.

00:39:25.390 --> 00:39:28.820
We have the chief
rabbi, Herman Adler.

00:39:28.820 --> 00:39:32.960
We have a whole range of people.

00:39:32.960 --> 00:39:35.780
We have [inaudible]
my list of them.

00:39:35.780 --> 00:39:40.400
We have a 66-line stanza
with all these people on it,

00:39:40.400 --> 00:39:44.220
with the chief rabbi, with the
Zionist Ahada Ahm [phonetic],

00:39:44.220 --> 00:39:46.330
with the anarchist
leader Rudolf Rocker,

00:39:46.330 --> 00:39:50.310
and it tells them what will
happen to all these people

00:39:50.310 --> 00:39:54.500
at the end of time when White
Chapels turns upside down.

00:39:54.500 --> 00:39:57.050
So the chief rabbi will
stand down and questions

00:39:57.050 --> 00:39:59.970
and rulings will be taken to
the secular Zionist Ahada Ahm.

00:39:59.970 --> 00:40:03.260
Anarchist leader Rudulf Rocker
will become an inspector

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:04.900
of kosher meat.

00:40:04.900 --> 00:40:06.600
The main Yiddish play
[inaudible] are expressed

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:08.980
in the Yiddish [inaudible]
would switch to English,

00:40:08.980 --> 00:40:11.580
and the new editor would be
Winston Churchill and so on.

00:40:11.580 --> 00:40:13.750
So it's a big satire.

00:40:13.750 --> 00:40:16.970
Now what connection this
has to religion, as I say,

00:40:16.970 --> 00:40:20.230
it's pretty tangential, but
what it's doing is it's using a

00:40:20.230 --> 00:40:24.050
structure and it's saying
really that, first of all,

00:40:24.050 --> 00:40:29.450
it's saying it's belittling the
tone of the Ezekiel [inaudible]

00:40:29.450 --> 00:40:33.130
but it's also, if you like,
saying that if you use a tone

00:40:33.130 --> 00:40:35.950
like that on these silly
little happenings happening

00:40:35.950 --> 00:40:39.360
in White Chapel, then
White Chapel is already

00:40:39.360 --> 00:40:43.200
such a topsy-turvy place where
everything is going wrong,

00:40:43.200 --> 00:40:48.370
there should really be a war to
end all wars to turn it right.

00:40:48.370 --> 00:40:52.480
But finally, I'm going to
finish on one more musical song.

00:40:52.480 --> 00:40:59.690
And this is a musical song by
Nager, and people use religion

00:40:59.690 --> 00:41:01.040
in lots of different ways,

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:03.850
but this is a particularly
interesting use of it

00:41:03.850 --> 00:41:08.100
because in the musical you
have a mixture of people who go

00:41:08.100 --> 00:41:11.260
to the music hall,
they're not all atheists

00:41:11.260 --> 00:41:13.000
like the socialists.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:16.300
Possibly very few of
them are, in fact.

00:41:16.300 --> 00:41:18.520
Some of them have
become secular.

00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:21.250
A lot of them would have had
a real feeling of nostalgia

00:41:21.250 --> 00:41:25.760
for religion and would have
had a real feeling of loss,

00:41:25.760 --> 00:41:29.530
and so what they did in the
musical was they did two things.

00:41:29.530 --> 00:41:32.910
They sort of engaged with
that loss at the same time

00:41:32.910 --> 00:41:38.040
as making fun, but also engaging
with the fact that the religion

00:41:38.040 --> 00:41:41.980
that the immigrants have was
very different to the religion

00:41:41.980 --> 00:41:45.520
that the Anglo-Jews had and
that they couldn't connect.

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:49.690
So, I'll just have a look
at the first verse of this

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:51.540
and then sing a couple
of verses of it,

00:41:51.540 --> 00:41:54.510
and hopefully you're
going to join in.

00:41:54.510 --> 00:41:58.720
Because this song called
Freg kayn katshanes,

00:41:58.720 --> 00:42:02.300
in a nice [inaudible] accent,
really Freg nit kayn katshanes,

00:42:02.300 --> 00:42:06.070
as in Anglan, Don't Ask Silly
Questions, this is England.

00:42:06.070 --> 00:42:08.540
So we'll have a look
at the chorus.

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:11.940
So it goes freg kayn katshanes,
and you have to all do

00:42:11.940 --> 00:42:16.070
in your best football sort
of like, football sort

00:42:16.070 --> 00:42:19.150
of way go, es iz England.

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:20.450
Okay, shall we try that.

00:42:20.450 --> 00:42:26.070
And freg nit kayn
katshanes, es iz England.

00:42:26.070 --> 00:42:28.960
Vos toyg mir di tanes,
es iz England.

00:42:28.960 --> 00:42:35.250
A medinele a shmatinke,
oy vey size tatinke.

00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:37.320
Ales is kapoyer do geshtelt.

00:42:37.320 --> 00:42:42.670
And you have to put your hand
in the air and go England.

00:42:42.670 --> 00:42:43.970
Right. England.

00:42:43.970 --> 00:42:47.250
Freg nit kayn katshanes, es iz
England [singing] es iz England.

00:42:47.250 --> 00:42:49.090
A medinele mit minhugimlekh.

00:42:49.090 --> 00:42:55.000
Un modne menshelekh, bekitser,
bekitser s'iz a lebedike velt.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:58.690
So we now get a view of
a man with his hat on

00:42:58.690 --> 00:43:01.930
and his [inaudible] and his
beard, and he comes over here

00:43:01.930 --> 00:43:04.410
and he says, I thought it was
going to be religious in England

00:43:04.410 --> 00:43:08.000
but what happens is
it's just too difficult.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:12.420
The religion sort of like
doesn't fit in with English life

00:43:12.420 --> 00:43:16.310
because if you have to work, you
have to be in the sweat shops.

00:43:16.310 --> 00:43:17.700
There's no where to pray.

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:19.230
You're praying there,
and you have

00:43:19.230 --> 00:43:21.100
to often be there
on the Sabbath.

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:27.660
And the second character that
we have is we have his neighbor

00:43:27.660 --> 00:43:31.180
who is already an Anglicized
Jew, and his neighbor is saying,

00:43:31.180 --> 00:43:35.570
no, you know, you can't even
expect that es iz England.

00:43:35.570 --> 00:43:39.510
So we'll have a look at the
second and third verses.

00:43:39.510 --> 00:44:43.110
[ Singing ]

00:44:43.110 --> 00:44:47.290
And, freg nit kayn
katshanes, es iz England.

00:44:47.290 --> 00:44:50.990
Vos toyg mir di tanes,
es iz England.

00:44:50.990 --> 00:44:57.830
A medinele a shmatinke,
oy vey size tatinke.

00:44:57.830 --> 00:45:00.920
Ales is kapoyer do geshtelt.

00:45:00.920 --> 00:45:03.560
England. Freg nit kayn
katshanes, es iz England.

00:45:03.560 --> 00:45:05.390
Es iz England.

00:45:05.390 --> 00:45:06.720
A medinele mit minhugimlekh.

00:45:06.720 --> 00:45:14.510
Un modne menshelekh, bekitser,
bekitser s'iz a lebedike velt.

00:45:14.510 --> 00:45:39.090
[ Singing ]

00:45:39.090 --> 00:45:42.940
And then we have the
neighbor again repeating it,

00:45:42.940 --> 00:45:45.120
come on, this is England.

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:47.620
So you see, the nature
of what's happening

00:45:47.620 --> 00:45:51.540
to religion is brought up, and
I guess the way it brings it

00:45:51.540 --> 00:45:54.470
up both by making fun
of it and treating it

00:45:54.470 --> 00:45:59.280
in a more serious way is sort
of shows the double things

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:00.750
that are going on for people.

00:46:00.750 --> 00:46:04.460
Maybe they move their
religion because they're having

00:46:04.460 --> 00:46:05.760
to work all the time
and [inaudible]

00:46:05.760 --> 00:46:07.690
and maybe they feel a
little bit guilty about it.

00:46:07.690 --> 00:46:10.530
You've got a lot
of varying degrees

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:12.680
of what people are
feeling about it.

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:20.030
So, this has been a tiny
little glimpse of what you got.

00:46:20.030 --> 00:46:23.000
There are a hundred
texts analyzed or looked

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:27.550
at in the book that engage
with British culture.

00:46:27.550 --> 00:46:31.430
During that time, I found 300
texts, and all these texts are

00:46:31.430 --> 00:46:37.180
in rhyming couplets,
and it's an archive

00:46:37.180 --> 00:46:39.470
that has barely been touched,

00:46:39.470 --> 00:46:42.580
and as any Yiddish [inaudible]
will tell you here in the states

00:46:42.580 --> 00:46:46.480
as well, that there's a huge
archive here in America as well,

00:46:46.480 --> 00:46:51.190
and again, the sort of research
that has been done on it is only

00:46:51.190 --> 00:46:54.310
like touching the surface
of it, and that, you know,

00:46:54.310 --> 00:46:56.290
there's lots and
lots more to do.

00:46:56.290 --> 00:46:58.450
So a lot of encouragement
for people, please,

00:46:58.450 --> 00:47:01.190
to become Yiddish and
do some of this research

00:47:01.190 --> 00:47:04.600
because the social histories
they give us are very real

00:47:04.600 --> 00:47:07.060
or very interesting, and
there are lots and lots

00:47:07.060 --> 00:47:10.470
of connections, both
with Jewish immigrants

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:14.880
in just different places and
with immigrant culture in London

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:17.280
between the different,
or but in other places,

00:47:17.280 --> 00:47:20.800
between the different immigrant
communities in those places.

00:47:20.800 --> 00:47:24.470
So I feel that this sort of work
actually does lay the ground

00:47:24.470 --> 00:47:26.520
work for a lot of
other things to come.

00:47:26.520 --> 00:47:28.510
And thank you for being
a lovely audience.

00:47:28.510 --> 00:47:33.540
[ Applause ]

00:47:33.540 --> 00:47:36.000
Yeah, so are there
any questions?

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:37.800
Yeah?

00:47:37.800 --> 00:48:00.150
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:48:00.150 --> 00:48:01.600
Oh, well that's very,
very interesting,

00:48:01.600 --> 00:48:03.130
because I haven't heard
what you just told me now.

00:48:03.130 --> 00:48:06.110
So, first of all der blofer.

00:48:06.110 --> 00:48:10.140
The word blofer in Yiddish
has got a stronger meaning

00:48:10.140 --> 00:48:11.440
than in English.

00:48:11.440 --> 00:48:13.980
So the word blofer is
like to hoodwink someone.

00:48:13.980 --> 00:48:16.110
It doesn't have the same clout.

00:48:16.110 --> 00:48:17.810
Now, sometimes it's used gently,

00:48:17.810 --> 00:48:20.390
but actually blofer
means cheating and lying.

00:48:20.390 --> 00:48:22.580
So, yeah, it's a bad thing.

00:48:22.580 --> 00:48:24.170
And I mean a pretty
bad thing in English,

00:48:24.170 --> 00:48:25.820
but it's got a gentler
side to it.

00:48:25.820 --> 00:48:28.260
But in Yiddish it's
not a nice thing.

00:48:28.260 --> 00:48:31.800
And der blofer the
magazine had a byline

00:48:31.800 --> 00:48:36.520
which read [foreign language
spoken], everyone lies,

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:37.820
[foreign language spoken].

00:48:37.820 --> 00:48:44.360
The blofer comes
to tell the truth.

00:48:44.360 --> 00:48:48.020
And so it's very
curious, you saying,

00:48:48.020 --> 00:48:50.910
because obviously a blofer
can't really tell the truth,

00:48:50.910 --> 00:48:54.000
they're bluffing people, so
it's sort of saying like, okay,

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:55.310
so we're now going
to have double bluffs

00:48:55.310 --> 00:48:57.620
and triple bluffs going on here.

00:48:57.620 --> 00:49:01.310
But the nature of that magazine
was to expose hypocrisy,

00:49:01.310 --> 00:49:05.060
and in fact, there's a very
interesting column that happens

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:06.470
on a number of issues called
[foreign language spoken],

00:49:06.470 --> 00:49:08.380
the blofer laughed.

00:49:08.380 --> 00:49:11.840
And what it does is it picks
out all these instances

00:49:11.840 --> 00:49:15.890
of hypocrisy, and then the
blofer goes ah ha ha ha ha.

00:49:15.890 --> 00:49:18.170
And throws his head
back and laughs.

00:49:18.170 --> 00:49:23.530
So, the instances of hypocrisy
might be someone is getting

00:49:23.530 --> 00:49:27.970
married and the people in the
family go to Eastern Europe,

00:49:27.970 --> 00:49:30.950
bring their wife
over and bring her

00:49:30.950 --> 00:49:33.430
to the [foreign language
spoken].

00:49:33.430 --> 00:49:37.440
Or the blofer is saying, what
you get a sense of in this,

00:49:37.440 --> 00:49:39.880
so that's [inaudible]
that's generic yeah,

00:49:39.880 --> 00:49:44.270
but then you get the blofer
talking about a certain lord

00:49:44.270 --> 00:49:47.420
who will pay his coachman,
his non-Jewish coachman,

00:49:47.420 --> 00:49:53.080
substantial bonuses but will
not support a Jewish hospital.

00:49:53.080 --> 00:49:55.720
And this was a particular story.

00:49:55.720 --> 00:49:58.240
Maybe not that he was paying
his non-Jewish coachman service,

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:01.570
but was saying that he won't
support Jewish things even

00:50:01.570 --> 00:50:04.320
thought he is a Jew,
Lord Rothchild,

00:50:04.320 --> 00:50:07.600
but he will support
non-Jewish things because he was

00:50:07.600 --> 00:50:11.590
so terrified of anti-Semitism
that he was, or the situation

00:50:11.590 --> 00:50:14.190
of Jews in England, that
he would sort of fall

00:50:14.190 --> 00:50:18.050
over backwards not to
support Jews was what this

00:50:18.050 --> 00:50:19.350
statement said.

00:50:19.350 --> 00:50:20.650
And the blofer is laughing.

00:50:20.650 --> 00:50:25.050
So, they're making fun of things
that are real in the community,

00:50:25.050 --> 00:50:28.200
and they're making
fun of generic things.

00:50:28.200 --> 00:50:32.450
So, yes, the concept of
blofer, being a blofer,

00:50:32.450 --> 00:50:35.860
I think is really, really
important, and I get the sense

00:50:35.860 --> 00:50:40.140
that there's a huge amount of
satire being written in Yiddish,

00:50:40.140 --> 00:50:44.080
and in a way, satire is trying
to do that, is trying to show

00:50:44.080 --> 00:50:46.420
where the hypocrisy
lies, is trying to show

00:50:46.420 --> 00:50:49.460
where people are being too
[inaudible] and double minded

00:50:49.460 --> 00:50:51.750
and saying one thing
and doing another.

00:50:51.750 --> 00:50:54.430
And so it's coming up
over and over again.

00:50:54.430 --> 00:50:56.340
So I think it's very
interesting that you say

00:50:56.340 --> 00:50:59.870
that England is being seen
as the land of hypocrisy,

00:50:59.870 --> 00:51:04.100
and certainly the Yiddish
satirists are pushing, you know,

00:51:04.100 --> 00:51:06.140
trying to show where that is.

00:51:06.140 --> 00:51:09.150
In fact, even in very
interesting stuff in the '40s

00:51:09.150 --> 00:51:11.930
and '50s, they're still
writing Yiddish satire.

00:51:11.930 --> 00:51:13.730
Yeah?

00:51:13.730 --> 00:51:25.040
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:51:25.040 --> 00:51:26.340
All right.

00:51:26.340 --> 00:51:27.640
So there's different publishers

00:51:27.640 --> 00:51:28.940
for all these different
things, yeah.

00:51:28.940 --> 00:51:30.490
So the socialist publishers,

00:51:30.490 --> 00:51:33.660
they are producing
their own presses,

00:51:33.660 --> 00:51:35.490
because they really
can't get anyone else

00:51:35.490 --> 00:51:36.790
to publish their material.

00:51:36.790 --> 00:51:39.880
So they're getting their press,
they've got, for example,

00:51:39.880 --> 00:51:41.180
the [foreign language spoken],

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:42.660
which was the main
socialist paper,

00:51:42.660 --> 00:51:47.000
was being published
by their own press.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:51.450
Then it would get defaced,
and people would break in

00:51:51.450 --> 00:51:54.360
and smash the printing presses

00:51:54.360 --> 00:51:56.340
and they'd have to
like get new ones.

00:51:56.340 --> 00:51:58.890
So that's what's
happening there.

00:51:58.890 --> 00:52:01.410
So what that shows and what we
write about is there's loads

00:52:01.410 --> 00:52:03.790
of politics around publishing.

00:52:03.790 --> 00:52:08.260
Then, the more mainstream
papers are also having their

00:52:08.260 --> 00:52:09.560
own presses.

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:12.620
The smaller things, so
the socialist pamphlets

00:52:12.620 --> 00:52:14.640
and stuff are also
being published

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:15.940
by the [foreign language
spoken] press.

00:52:15.940 --> 00:52:17.760
So all of that is in one place.

00:52:17.760 --> 00:52:22.020
The Song Book, there are a
number of different publishers.

00:52:22.020 --> 00:52:23.660
So there's a publisher
called Mazin [phonetic].

00:52:23.660 --> 00:52:25.210
There's a publisher
called Josef [phonetic].

00:52:25.210 --> 00:52:26.660
There's a publisher called
Wooderman [phonetic].

00:52:26.660 --> 00:52:29.860
And they're all producing
song sheets.

00:52:29.860 --> 00:52:34.700
And they're selling them
sort of for a penny.

00:52:34.700 --> 00:52:38.210
And then Josef the
publisher, in fact,

00:52:38.210 --> 00:52:39.690
there's another song called
[foreign language spoken],

00:52:39.690 --> 00:52:42.440
which was what we saw earlier,

00:52:42.440 --> 00:52:47.970
and he uses that to advertise
his publishing services

00:52:47.970 --> 00:52:53.310
for songs, and he says, I've
go this great, new invention.

00:52:53.310 --> 00:52:56.290
I've got a song book,
not just a song sheet,

00:52:56.290 --> 00:52:58.930
and he's connecting all of these
and putting them into a book.

00:52:58.930 --> 00:53:02.170
So, these people are realizing
there's a commercial market

00:53:02.170 --> 00:53:03.470
out there, okay.

00:53:03.470 --> 00:53:05.200
So there's the song sheets
that people get for a penny,

00:53:05.200 --> 00:53:06.770
but if you do it in a
book, you get even more,

00:53:06.770 --> 00:53:08.280
and they're putting
little pictures

00:53:08.280 --> 00:53:10.060
of people's faces on them.

00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:13.330
So they're really
playing to the market.

00:53:13.330 --> 00:53:19.500
And I guess that what's
happening quite a lot is a lot

00:53:19.500 --> 00:53:23.710
of these publications will run
for quite short lengths of time

00:53:23.710 --> 00:53:26.910
because financially it's really
hard to keep them viable.

00:53:26.910 --> 00:53:30.660
So you've got lots of
competing presses and small ones

00:53:30.660 --> 00:53:32.520
and slightly larger ones.

00:53:32.520 --> 00:53:35.300
The thing about like
Mazin, so ones, and Josef,

00:53:35.300 --> 00:53:37.120
the ones who are
producing the song sheets,

00:53:37.120 --> 00:53:38.880
on one side they're
producing these song sheets.

00:53:38.880 --> 00:53:42.660
On the other side they're
producing like Zionist songs

00:53:42.660 --> 00:53:49.810
about sort of the new Zionist
movements that produces,

00:53:49.810 --> 00:53:54.200
for example, Josef produces
a series of songs to the tune

00:53:54.200 --> 00:53:56.020
of [foreign language
spoken] in Yiddish.

00:53:56.020 --> 00:54:01.600
A and then also they're
producing religious stuff

00:54:01.600 --> 00:54:02.900
as well.

00:54:02.900 --> 00:54:06.510
So, I mean I find it sort
of like quite strange

00:54:06.510 --> 00:54:09.090
that at the same time this
publisher is producing these

00:54:09.090 --> 00:54:10.990
silly sexy musical lyrics

00:54:10.990 --> 00:54:13.860
and then also producing some
quite religious material.

00:54:13.860 --> 00:54:15.160
But that's what's happening.

00:54:15.160 --> 00:54:18.940
There are a number of
publishers doing that.

00:54:21.210 --> 00:54:23.510
Yes?

00:54:36.040 --> 00:54:38.590
Well, I mean it's interesting

00:54:38.590 --> 00:54:40.960
because [inaudible] has always
tried to be quite trendy,

00:54:40.960 --> 00:54:44.430
and so it's set in the present
time, but it is in the east end,

00:54:44.430 --> 00:54:47.560
so it is in this area or a
little bit further east maybe.

00:54:47.560 --> 00:54:50.780
The trendiness has meant
that it has sort of brought

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:53.610
in immigrants occasionally
because [inaudible] it was

00:54:53.610 --> 00:54:57.470
like a very much a non-immigrant
population as it was engaging

00:54:57.470 --> 00:55:02.310
with sort of the white east
enders who had been born there

00:55:02.310 --> 00:55:04.650
and had lived there
for generations.

00:55:04.650 --> 00:55:09.910
But it's certainly in this area,
and so it's engaging with some

00:55:09.910 --> 00:55:12.200
of the issues around work.

00:55:12.200 --> 00:55:18.580
And I think it's interesting you
bring that up, because in a way,

00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:21.300
I think it became very popular

00:55:21.300 --> 00:55:25.590
because the east end has been
home to all sorts of waves

00:55:25.590 --> 00:55:28.190
of immigrants as they came
in and then often they moved

00:55:28.190 --> 00:55:31.290
out as they became
more upwardly mobile.

00:55:31.290 --> 00:55:33.940
So the here were the
Irish before the Jews

00:55:33.940 --> 00:55:36.880
and then the Jews, and then
we've had Banglandeshian,

00:55:36.880 --> 00:55:38.180
Somolian.

00:55:38.180 --> 00:55:41.970
And so it's become an
area that has been sort

00:55:41.970 --> 00:55:46.770
of an immigrant area as well
as an indigenous population

00:55:46.770 --> 00:55:49.040
of white British people.

00:55:49.040 --> 00:55:54.280
So there's a sort of
sentimentalism that goes

00:55:54.280 --> 00:55:56.290
with the east end
and that has sort

00:55:56.290 --> 00:55:58.680
of like been drawn around it.

00:55:58.680 --> 00:56:02.760
And I think that in a
way that's why something

00:56:02.760 --> 00:56:05.070
like east enders has got such a,

00:56:05.070 --> 00:56:09.970
just by its title has got quite
a powerful resonance for people.

